{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
The Indiana procedure for pretrial commitment of incompetent criminal defendants set forth in Ind.Ann.Stat. s 9\u8212\'3f1706a provides that a trial judge with \u8216\'3freasonable ground\u8217\'3f to believe the defendant to be incompetent to stand trial must appoint two examining physicians and schedule a competency hearing, at which the defendant may introduce evidence. If the court, on the basis of the physicians\rquote  report and \u8216\'3fother evidence,\u8217\'3f finds that the defendant lacks \u8216\'3fcomprehension sufficient to understand the proceedings and make his defense,\u8217\'3f the trial is delayed and the defendant is remanded to the state department of mental health for commitment to an \u8216\'3fappropriate psychiatric institution\u8217\'3f until defendant shall become \u8216\'3fsane.\u8217\'3f Other statutory provisions apply to commitment of citizens who are \u8216\'3ffeeble-minded, and are therefore unable properly to care for themselves.\u8217\'3f The procedures for committing such persons are substantially similar to those for determining a criminal defendant\rquote s pretrial competency, but a person committed as \u8216\'3ffeeble-minded\u8217\'3f may be released \u8216\'3fat any time\u8217\'3f his condition warrants it in the judgment of the superintendent of the institution. Indians also has a comprehensive commitment scheme for the \u8216\'3fmentally ill, i.e., those with a \u8216\'3fpsychiatric disorder\u8217\'3f as defined by the statute, who can be committed on a showing of mental illness and need for \u8216\'3fcare, treatment, training or detention.\u8217\'3f A person so committed may be released when the superintendent of the institution shall discharge him, or when he is cured.
\par 
}
}
}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
