Petitioner\rquote s central contention is that the State, in seeking in effect to commit him to a mental institution indefinitely, should have been required to invoke the standards and procedures of Ind.Ann.Stat. s 22\u8212\'3f1907, now Ind.Code 16\u8212\'3f15\u8212\'3f1\u8212\'3f3 (1971), governing commitment of \u8216\'3ffeeble-minded\u8217\'3f persons. That section provides that upon application of a \u8216\'3freputable citizen of the county\u8217\'3f and accompanying certificate of a reputable physician that a person is \u8216\'3ffeeble-minded and is not insane or epileptic\u8217\'3f (emphasis supplied), a circuit court judge shall appoint two physicians to examine such person. After notice, a hearing is held at which the patient is entitled to be represented by counsel. If the judge determines that the individual is indeed \u8216\'3ffeeble-minded,\u8217\'3f he enters an order of commitment and directs the clerk of the court to apply for the person\rquote s admission \u8216\'3fto the superintendent of the institution for feebleminded persons located in the district in which said county is situated.\u8217\'3f A person committed under this section may be released \u8216\'3fat any time,\u8217\'3f provided that \u8216\'3fin the judgment of the superintendent, the 
